  <hr/>

  <h2>Executive summary</h2>
  <p class="rlede">Dentistry's relationship with insurance is fracturing — and the practices that build a cash-pay membership base now will own the patients everyone else is about to lose. Five findings frame the 2026 opportunity:</p>
  <ol class="rfindings">
    <li><strong>The cash-pay population is structural, not marginal.</strong> 72 million U.S. adults — about 27%, nearly three times the medically uninsured — have no dental insurance.<sup>1</sup></li>
    <li><strong>The insurance relationship is fracturing.</strong> 29% of dentists dropped at least one insurance network in 2025, and another 15% say they're "very likely" to in 2026 — against a backdrop of 37 state dental-insurance-reform laws passed in 2025 and flat real reimbursement.<sup>2,3</sup></li>
    <li><strong>Dental leaders see the opportunity.</strong> In Clerri's survey of 105 dental leaders, 96% reported that 10-30% of their patients are uninsured or underinsured, and 81% saw meaningful cash-pay revenue upside.<sup>4</sup></li>
    <li><strong>But only 19% can capture it.</strong> Just one in five has a standardized way to convert that population — an infrastructure gap, not a demand gap. For a 25-location group, that gap can represent roughly $10M in lost lifetime revenue at a 10% attrition rate.<sup>4</sup></li>
    <li><strong>Where membership runs well, the economics are decisive.</strong> Enrolled patients produce $1,276/year vs. $469 for the uninsured, complete 5.9 vs. 2.4 procedures annually, and drive a 51% cash-production lift over two years.<sup>5</sup></li>
  </ol>

  <hr/>

  <h2>1 · The macro shift — why now</h2>
  <p>For two decades, the unspoken deal in dentistry was that insurance brought volume worth the discount. That math is breaking.</p>
  <p>Start with the population. <strong>72 million American adults — roughly 27% — have no dental insurance</strong>, nearly three times the number who lack medical coverage (CareQuest Institute, <em>State of Oral Health Equity in America</em>, 2024).<sup>1</sup> This isn't a fringe segment a practice can ignore; it's better than one in four adult patients walking through the door.</p>
  <p>Now the supply side. Dentists are voting with their contracts: <strong>29% dropped at least one insurance network in 2025, and 15% report they're "very likely" to drop one in 2026</strong> (ADA Health Policy Institute, <em>Economic Outlook &amp; Emerging Issues in Dentistry</em>, Q4 2025).<sup>2</sup> Inflation-adjusted PPO reimbursement has been flat to declining, even as roughly 74% of general dentists still participate in at least one PPO.<sup>2</sup></p>
  <p>And the regulatory ground is moving with them: <strong>37 dental-insurance-reform laws passed across 18 states in 2025 alone</strong> (ADA News, 2025)<sup>3</sup> — a wave of legislative pressure on the carriers that signals how strained the model has become.</p>
  <p class="rtakeaway">The takeaway: a large, permanent cash-pay population, a profession actively loosening its dependence on carriers, and a regulatory environment turning against the status quo. The question for every practice and group is no longer <em>whether</em> to build a non-insurance revenue stream — it's whether they'll build it before their competitor does.</p>

  <h2>2 · What dental leaders told us <span class="rtag">first-party research</span></h2>
  <p>To size the opportunity from the inside, Clerri surveyed <strong>105 dental leaders</strong> — the majority representing groups and DSOs.<sup>4</sup> Three findings stood out:</p>
  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="rstat"><div class="rnum">96%</div><div class="rlbl">said 10-30% of their patients are uninsured or underinsured</div></div>
    <div class="rstat"><div class="rnum">81%</div><div class="rlbl">saw meaningful cash-pay revenue upside in that population</div></div>
    <div class="rstat"><div class="rnum">19%</div><div class="rlbl">have a standardized way to actually capture it</div></div>
  </div>
  <p>The gap between 81% and 19% is the entire story. The demand is understood. The intent is there. What's missing is the <strong>infrastructure</strong> to convert an uninsured patient into a recurring member — consistently, across every location, without leaning on a busy front desk to "sell."</p>
  <p>At scale, that gap is expensive. For a 25-location group, a 10% attrition rate on uninsured patients who never get a membership offer represents on the order of <strong>$10M in lost lifetime revenue</strong>.<sup>4</sup> The opportunity isn't a marketing problem to be solved with more ads — it's an operational one, solved with a system.</p>

  <h2>3 · The economics of membership <span class="rtag">Clerri analysis</span></h2>
  <p>When practices do put that system in place, the per-patient economics are not subtle. In an analysis tracking the same cash-pay patients for two years before and after enrolling in a membership plan, Clerri (formerly Kleer) found:<sup>5</sup></p>
  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="rstat"><div class="rnum">$1,276</div><div class="rlbl">annual production per membership patient vs. $469 for the uninsured</div></div>
    <div class="rstat"><div class="rnum">5.9</div><div class="rlbl">procedures/year per member vs. 2.4 for the uninsured</div></div>
    <div class="rstat"><div class="rnum">+51%</div><div class="rlbl">cash production lift over two years</div></div>
  </div>
  <p>The mechanism is straightforward: a membership patient has already decided to invest in their care, so they show up more, accept more treatment, and stay. They convert an unpredictable, price-sensitive walk-in into a recurring relationship the practice controls — at a fee schedule the practice sets, not a carrier.</p>

  <h2>4 · The infrastructure gap — and the trap</h2>
  <p>If the opportunity is this clear, why does only 19% capture it? Two reasons.</p>
  <p><strong>First, it's been left to the front desk.</strong> The point of conversion — chairside, at checkout — sits with staff who are slammed with insurance admin and turn over frequently. Asking them to also "sell" membership, without a system, is why most plans stall.</p>
  <p><strong>Second, the DIY trap.</strong> Many practices that do act build a plan themselves — a spreadsheet, a discount, a handshake. But in most states a dental membership plan is a regulated product. Run without proper licensing (a DMPO structure), the right patient agreements, and a discount design that respects anti-kickback rules, an in-house plan exposes the practice to fines or worse.<sup>6</sup> The "free" plan carries the liability the practice can least afford.</p>
  <p class="rtakeaway">The practices winning the cash-pay shift aren't the ones with the most sales-savvy front desk or the cleverest spreadsheet. They're the ones who put a compliant, standardized system between the patient and the offer — so conversion happens reliably, at scale, without betting on individual heroics or accepting regulatory risk.</p>

  <h2>Methodology &amp; limitations</h2>
  <p class="rmethod">Clerri's leader survey (Findings §2) reflects responses from 105 dental leaders, weighted toward groups and DSOs; figures are self-reported and the sample is modest, so they are best read as directional sentiment from senior operators rather than a census. The membership-economics figures (§3) come from Clerri's (formerly Kleer's) internal analysis of cash-pay patients tracked two years pre- and post-enrollment; this is first-party industry analysis, not independent research. Third-party figures (§1) are cited to their original sources below. Where a commonly-circulated statistic could not be tied to an authoritative source, it was excluded.</p>

  <h2>Sources</h2>
  <ol class="rsources">
    <li>CareQuest Institute for Oral Health, <em>State of Oral Health Equity in America</em> (2024) — 72M U.S. adults (~27%) lack dental insurance. NORC survey, 9,000+ adults. <span class="vmono">carequest.org</span></li>
    <li>ADA Health Policy Institute, <em>Economic Outlook &amp; Emerging Issues in Dentistry</em>, Q4 2025 — 29% dropped a network in 2025; 15% "very likely" in 2026; ~74% PPO participation; flat real reimbursement. <span class="vmono">ada.org/resources/research/health-policy-institute</span></li>
    <li>ADA News, "37 dental insurance reform laws passed in 2025" (Oct 2025) — 37 laws across 18 states. <span class="vmono">adanews.ada.org</span></li>
    <li>Clerri / Becker's Dental + DSO Review leader survey (Feb 2026), n=105 <span class="vmono">(confirm exact figures + n before print)</span>. <span class="vmono">groupdentistrynow.com · clerri.com</span></li>
    <li>Clerri (formerly Kleer), "Data Validates the ROI of Dental Membership Plans" (2025) — first-party analysis <span class="vmono">(confirm sample size before print)</span>. <span class="vmono">kleer.com/blog</span></li>
    <li>State DMPO / membership-plan compliance requirements vary by state; in-house plans without proper licensing carry regulatory exposure. <span class="vmono">(legal to confirm jurisdictions before publishing specifics)</span></li>
  </ol>
  <p class="mono muted" style="font-size:0.72rem">Excluded as unverifiable/vendor-only: a specific "% underinsured" count; "40% of practices offer a membership plan"; "35% planning to drop PPOs" (use the ADA HPI figures instead). NADP reports ~87% of the total U.S. population had some dental coverage in 2023 — a different denominator (all ages, incl. Medicaid/Medicare) than the CareQuest adults-only figure; don't present the two side by side.</p>

